  "prompt": "How is the ACLU funded? How are the funds used?",
  "response": "The ACLU (American Civil Liberties Union) is primarily funded through:\n\n1. Membership dues\n- Individual memberships contribute regular financial support\n\n2. Individual donations\n- Private citizens make one-time or recurring financial contributions\n\n3. Foundation grants\n- Various philanthropic foundations provide funding\n\n4. Planned giving and bequests\n- Some supporters include the ACLU in their estate plans\n\nFunds are typically used for:\n\n1. Legal activities\n- Filing lawsuits\n- Defending civil rights cases\n- Supporting legal challenges to legislation\n- Providing legal representation\n\n2. Advocacy and policy work\n- Lobbying for civil rights legislation\n- Public education campaigns\n- Producing policy reports\n\n3. Organizational operations\n- Staff salaries\n- Administrative expenses\n- Office maintenance\n- Fundraising efforts\n\n4. Local and national chapter support\n- Funding state and regional ACLU offices\n- Supporting grassroots organizing\n\n5. Research and documentation\n- Investigating civil rights issues\n- Documenting potential rights violations\n\nThe organization is a nonprofit and maintains financial transparency, regularly publishing annual reports detailing its income and expenditures. They do not accept government funding to maintain independence in their advocacy work.",
